@scoder Thank you for pointing me to this issue. I did try searching for it, but I didn't see it. I'd like to try working on it as I get the time.

I'm not sure I fully understand the reasons behind the current implementation, though. As far as I can tell, it first attempts to find a matching Cython-space type name for each of the passed Python-object arguments and stores it in `dest_sig`, in the code generated by line `290` of `FusedNode.py` under `._fused_instance_checks()` (as well as analogues for other special-cased objects like Numpy arrays), and then it iterates through and parses the signature of every single available permutation of specializations (presumably at `O(k**n)`), in the code generated around line `700` under `make_fused_cpdef()`, to search for exact matches to the received arguments (with a check to ignore unmatched arguments that are still `None`).

Assuming that the signatures for all available specializations are known ahead of time, though, and seeing how it's more or less checking for exact matches between `dest_sig` and `signatures.keys()`, why is it not possible or viable to just directly generate the signature of the required specialization from the inferred types of the input arguments in `dest_sig`?
